at constitute global change. Through case studies that span from the labour flexibility debates in Britain and Germany, to the strategies and tactics of corporations and workers, the author examines how globalisation is interpreted and experienced in everyday life. Contestation, she argues, is about more than just direct protests and resistances. It has become a central feature of the practices that enable or confound global restructuring.This book offers students and scholars of international political economy, sociology and industrial relations an innovative framework for the analysis of globalisation and the restructuring of work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 0aInternational economic integrationxSocial aspects. 0aWorkxSocial aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh  acontestation.  aeveryday life.  aglobal change.  aglobal restructuring.  aglobalization.  alabour flexibility.  arestructuring of work.  asocial practices.  atactics of corporations.  aworkers.1 aAmoore, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137418zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137418zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137418/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA